Title: Capturing the Shape of Business Cycles with Nonlinear Autoregressive Leading 
    Indicator Models.
Author-Name: Athanasopoulos, G.
Author-X-Name-Last: Athanasopoulos
Author-X-Name-First: G.
Author-Name: Anderson, H.M.
Author-X-Name-Last: Anderson
Author-X-Name-First: H.M.
Author-Email: Heather.Anderson@BusEco.monash.edu.au
Author-Name: Vahid, F.
Author-X-Name-Last: Vahid
Author-X-Name-First: F.
Author-Email: Farshid.Vahid@BusEco.monash.edu.au
Keywords: Business Cycles; Leading Indicators; Nonlinear Models; Yield Spread
Length: 36 pages
Abstract: This paper studies linear and linear autoregressive leading indicator 
    models of business cycles in OECD countries. The models use the spread 
    between short-term and long-term interest rates as leading indicators
    for GDP, and their success in capturing business cycles gauged by the 
    non-parametric procedures developed by Harding and Pagan (2001). Our 
    preliminary findings indicate that bivariate nonlinear models of output and
    the interest rate spread can successfully capture the shape of the business 
    cycle. In particular, they can capture the features of recession and the 
    deviation of the actual path of the cycles from a triangular approximation 
    to this path, both characteristics that other models of GDP fail to reproduce.
